1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:02,960
I built a simple website that makes 40K a month.

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:04,240
This is Angus Chang.

3
00:00:04,240 --> 00:00:08,080
He lives in Hong Kong and he built the simplest website I've ever seen.

4
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:10,719
>> I built a website that literally does one thing.

5
00:00:10,719 --> 00:00:15,360
>> And what's even crazier is that he operates this business entirely as a solopreneur.

6
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:19,279
Solo founder, zero employees, 100% bootstrapped.

7
00:00:19,279 --> 00:00:21,680
>> I bootstrapped this entire business by myself.

8
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:28,320
>> I brought Angus onto the channel and he broke down how he found a silly idea that thousands of people also happen to need.

9
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:34,640
why spending money on ads actually hurt his business and why having a big strategy is for losers.

10
00:00:34,640 --> 00:00:35,840
All right, let's dive in.

11
00:00:35,840 --> 00:00:41,239
I'm Pat Walls and this is Starter Story.

12
00:00:41,680 --> 00:00:43,360
All right, welcome Angus to the channel.

13
00:00:43,360 --> 00:00:44,239
Thank you for coming on.

14
00:00:44,239 --> 00:00:47,120
Tell me about who you are, what you built, and what's your story.

15
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:48,160
>> My name is Angus Chang.

16
00:00:48,160 --> 00:00:50,160
I built a business that does just one thing.

17
00:00:50,160 --> 00:00:55,840
I launched it in 2021 and today it makes $40,000 a month and I run it entirely by myself.

18
00:00:55,840 --> 00:01:02,399
All right, before we get into the numbers of this amazing business that you built, I want to hear how did you come up with the idea for Bank Statement Converter?

19
00:01:02,399 --> 00:01:05,360
>> I had just quit my job and I knew I was going to build some sort of product.

20
00:01:05,360 --> 00:01:06,960
I actually had planned to build something else.

21
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:09,920
But on the side, I was thinking, you know, I've got X amount of money in the bank.

22
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:13,200
I want to know how long I can continue living the way I'm living.

23
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:15,680
And to do that, I wanted multiple years of bank data.

24
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:20,479
I wanted it all in a nice Excel spreadsheet so I can kind of figure out, okay, it looks like I'm spending this much a month.

25
00:01:20,479 --> 00:01:25,040
And that was a lot harder than I thought it would be because my bank only provided PDF bank statements.

26
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:29,840
So, I wrote some code to get the transaction data out of the bank statements and that was also really hard.

27
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:31,600
So, I figured it must be a real problem.

28
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:32,560
>> Okay, you found the idea.

29
00:01:32,560 --> 00:01:33,920
Lots of people have ideas all the time.

30
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:35,759
How did you know that this could be a business?

31
00:01:35,759 --> 00:01:41,280
>> Often I like to just make an MVP as quickly as possible, get it into production and then get it in front of real users.

32
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:42,240
And that's kind of what I did.

33
00:01:42,240 --> 00:01:44,400
So, me and a friend worked on it for about a week.

34
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:49,520
We got a domain, we launched it, and then we bought Google ads to get people to start clicking into the domain.

35
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:53,920
And immediately people started uploading bank statements, which kind of validated the problem.

36
00:01:53,920 --> 00:01:57,360
You know, >> I think a lot of people watching this will be looking for how do I find a simple idea?

37
00:01:57,360 --> 00:01:59,520
How do I find this kind of app that can do one thing?

38
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:01,840
I can build it myself and it can become a business.

39
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:04,719
Do you have any sort of framework or strategy around finding these ideas?

40
00:02:04,719 --> 00:02:08,800
>> I think a good way is if you encounter the problem yourself or a painoint yourself.

41
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:12,080
Another way is your colleagues or friends complain about stuff at work.

42
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:16,720
But sometimes I just get ideas and I just think of the smallest possible way to implement that idea.

43
00:02:16,720 --> 00:02:19,360
You know, get it out there and see if people will use it.

44
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:24,319
You can try to validate before launching, but if it takes you like one or two weeks to make an MVP,

45
00:02:24,319 --> 00:02:25,840
it's not that much of a risk anyway.

46
00:02:25,840 --> 00:02:27,440
So, you might as well just build it.

47
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:27,599
>> Okay.

48
00:02:27,599 --> 00:02:31,840
So, we talked about finding the idea, but I want to hear more about how you actually built this thing.

49
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:34,800
How did you go from idea to real live website?

50
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:38,080
>> When I proved this out, I had a local version that would work for my own bank.

51
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:39,120
I wrote this in Cotlin.

52
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:40,720
It was basically a console application.

53
00:02:40,720 --> 00:02:43,840
And then I generalized it a bit so that it would work with other bank statements.

54
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:55,200
Like obviously I don't know if it works for every bank statement but I tried it out with some of my other banks and some of my friends banks and then I convinced a friend to help me build the UI for this and he did this in Nex.js and then we got the two things deployed.

55
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:56,959
I got the front end on Netifi.

56
00:02:56,959 --> 00:03:01,440
I deployed the back end to uh EC2 on AWS and that's kind of how we did it.

57
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:01,840
>> Cool.

58
00:03:01,840 --> 00:03:05,519
You probably build a bunch of other apps and you learned a lot in the process of what works and what doesn't.

59
00:03:05,519 --> 00:03:07,280
What's your kind of framework for building?

60
00:03:07,280 --> 00:03:08,560
What's the Angus method?

61
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:10,560
>> It's kind of like a lean startup approach.

62
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:13,360
you know, you make an MVP, launch it as quickly as possible.

63
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:16,000
Try to get it in front of your target audience, whoever they are.

64
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,040
Don't show it to your friends and family, you know, they will just lie to you and they're probably not going to buy your product anyway.

65
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:24,000
And then you build your features based on real user feedback.

66
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,640
So maybe somebody emails you or maybe like analytics.

67
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:30,000
So if you notice that people are dropping off on this page, maybe you need to do something there.

68
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,840
If people are not using a certain feature, maybe don't continue working on it.

69
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:34,080
>> All right.

70
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:36,239
Well, let's get into some of the numbers of this.

71
00:03:36,239 --> 00:03:39,760
Can you give me a timeline of the growth of bank statement converter?

72
00:03:39,760 --> 00:03:42,239
So 2021 we launched bank statement converter.

73
00:03:42,239 --> 00:03:45,280
2022 we hit 6,000 USD MRR.

74
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:47,120
2023 14,000.

75
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:48,879
2024 27,000.

76
00:03:48,879 --> 00:03:51,360
And today it's at 40,000 USD MR.

77
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:53,200
>> Total number of users 75,000.

78
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:57,680
Paying customers about a,000 and traffic per month about 40,000.

79
00:03:57,680 --> 00:03:58,000
>> All right.

80
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,439
So everyone watching this right now is probably wondering, okay, it's cool how you built it,

81
00:04:01,439 --> 00:04:02,879
but how did you actually market it?

82
00:04:02,879 --> 00:04:04,000
How did you get customers?

83
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:07,360
Was there a specific strategy that made this thing go up?

84
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,120
>> At first, I bought Google search ads.

85
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:13,840
These were good for getting the initial users, but I was never able to run an ad campaign profitably.

86
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:19,120
So, I would spend maybe $1,000 on ads and bring in about $300 in sales.

87
00:04:19,120 --> 00:04:22,800
I spent a lot of time trying to optimize these ads, trying to get them more profitable,

88
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:24,000
but never really worked out.

89
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,919
I tried blogging and building in public.

90
00:04:25,919 --> 00:04:27,520
That gets quite a lot of attention.

91
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:32,800
However, I don't think I get many users from doing that because my users don't seem to be using Twitter or reading my blog.

92
00:04:32,800 --> 00:04:38,240
I also tried sending out cold emails and in 3 months of doing that, I got one sale and I also annoyed a lot of people.

93
00:04:38,240 --> 00:04:39,840
I got a lot of angry messages back.

94
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:41,120
People don't really like cold emails.

95
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:45,360
After about 6 months of running Google search ads, I decided, you know, I'm just not going to do this anymore.

96
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:46,960
I might not even do this app anymore.

97
00:04:46,960 --> 00:04:49,680
I cut the ads and I thought maybe go back to work.

98
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:52,320
And interestingly, I stopped paying for ads.

99
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:55,360
So, I knew everyone who was clicking on the website was an organic user.

100
00:04:55,360 --> 00:04:57,360
And I noticed I started getting new users.

101
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:59,680
I'd get like two or three new signups a day.

102
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:02,639
From that point on, I kind of focused on improving the products.

103
00:05:02,639 --> 00:05:05,840
When customers complained about things, I would fix them.

104
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:09,199
and I just basically focused on doing what the customers wanted.

105
00:05:09,199 --> 00:05:13,360
>> All right, real quick before we get into how Angus built this $30,000 per month business,

106
00:05:13,360 --> 00:05:17,600
let's talk about something that matters a lot once your business starts making money.

107
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:18,160
Banking.

108
00:05:18,160 --> 00:05:22,240
The truth is most banks aren't built for solo founders and SAS builders.

109
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:27,840
They slow you down with low card limits, delayed payments, and systems that feel like they were made in 2004.

110
00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:33,360
That's why we're partnering with Brex, the modern finance platform that's built from the ground up for startups.

111
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:37,199
With Brex, you can get up to 20x higher card limits.

112
00:05:37,199 --> 00:05:44,320
Earn high yields on your cash, automate expenses, invoices, and vendor payments, and move money instantly when you need it.

113
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:50,400
It's fast, flexible, and made to scale with you, no matter how small or scrappy your SAS is right now.

114
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:54,880
We worked with them to put together a free guide called The Startup's Guide to Modern Banking.

115
00:05:54,880 --> 00:06:00,320
It breaks down how to protect your cash, extend runway, and upgrade your finance stack without wasting time.

116
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:03,280
Just click the first link in the description to download it.

117
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:05,120
Thank you to Brex for supporting the channel.

118
00:06:05,120 --> 00:06:06,240
Let's get back to the video.

119
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:08,319
All right, so you got this website making a bunch of money.

120
00:06:08,319 --> 00:06:09,199
It's a great business.

121
00:06:09,199 --> 00:06:10,639
You have a team working on this.

122
00:06:10,639 --> 00:06:11,440
>> No, it's just me.

123
00:06:11,440 --> 00:06:14,639
I started this business with a friend, but he left after a few weeks.

124
00:06:14,639 --> 00:06:18,000
I do all the development, customer support, sales, and marketing.

125
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:18,240
>> All right.

126
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:22,319
So, you went from working a 9 toive job to being a soloreneur, running your own business.

127
00:06:22,319 --> 00:06:23,840
What was that transition like?

128
00:06:23,840 --> 00:06:28,400
working for a company, you kind of spend a lot of time like playing, you know, refactoring code,

129
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:30,080
trying out databases you think are cool.

130
00:06:30,080 --> 00:06:35,120
But when you work for yourself, you quickly realize these things don't make any money and potentially are a waste of time.

131
00:06:35,120 --> 00:06:36,560
So, your focus is really different.

132
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:43,199
You go from being like a developer who cares about writing nice code to a developer who cares about business features and more business aligned,

133
00:06:43,199 --> 00:06:43,840
I suppose.

134
00:06:43,840 --> 00:06:44,080
>> Yeah.

135
00:06:44,080 --> 00:06:49,120
In your experience becoming a solarreneur, what are some of the pros and cons of the solarreneur lifestyle?

136
00:06:49,120 --> 00:06:50,639
>> When I first started, it was a big change.

137
00:06:50,639 --> 00:06:54,000
Most of my friends I knew, most of the people I hung out with were people from work.

138
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,440
You know, you go out for drinks or whatever.

139
00:06:55,440 --> 00:06:59,919
And then I went to working for myself, just being at home all day, basically not socializing.

140
00:06:59,919 --> 00:07:06,560
It's kind of a big change when you go from making maybe like $10,000 a month to 200 a month and you're basically hanging out with no one.

141
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:08,800
So being a soloreneur can be pretty depressing.

142
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:12,400
Another thing is people often don't really get what you're doing, especially when you're failing to make money.

143
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:16,400
I remember in the first two years people didn't understand why I did it and they would also,

144
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:19,520
you know, hear the revenue and they would tell me, "Oh, this is like a crappy business.

145
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:20,400
you shouldn't go after this.

146
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:23,840
And then multiple years later when it's making a lot more money, those same people will say like,

147
00:07:23,840 --> 00:07:24,960
"Oh, it's a great business."

148
00:07:24,960 --> 00:07:26,800
Some pros, it's good to have your own schedule.

149
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:29,280
Often I wake up and go hiking instead of going to work.

150
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:31,759
It's nice to be like on a different schedule to everyone else.

151
00:07:31,759 --> 00:07:35,840
If you're starting up a VC back startup, you have a boss, you have investors, you got a lot of time pressure.

152
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:37,759
As a soloreneur, you can go a bit slower.

153
00:07:37,759 --> 00:07:41,840
I mean, depending on how much money you have saved up, and you can also go after much smaller markets.

154
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:45,120
A venture capitalist wouldn't want to invest in bank statement converter.

155
00:07:45,120 --> 00:07:46,000
It doesn't make enough money.

156
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:46,960
The market's not big enough.

157
00:07:46,960 --> 00:07:49,199
But for a single person, you know, it's enough, right?

158
00:07:49,199 --> 00:07:51,360
And you can be quite happy with that revenue.

159
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:51,680
>> Cool.

160
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:52,800
Now, you have this great business.

161
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:53,680
You're a solopreneur.

162
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:54,639
What were you doing before?

163
00:07:54,639 --> 00:07:55,520
Were you a developer?

164
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:57,840
What was your kind of journey to starting your own business?

165
00:07:57,840 --> 00:07:58,960
>> I've always been a developer.

166
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:01,599
In 2010, I worked for an EPS machine company.

167
00:08:01,599 --> 00:08:02,960
2010 to 2014.

168
00:08:02,960 --> 00:08:06,960
I worked for myself developing indie games for the Xbox Live indie game store.

169
00:08:06,960 --> 00:08:10,000
I also developed a virtual girlfriend app for Android and iOS.

170
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:11,120
It's called Girlfriend Plus.

171
00:08:11,120 --> 00:08:14,319
2017 to 2019, I worked in an investment bank in Hong Kong.

172
00:08:14,319 --> 00:08:16,400
2020 I worked at a crypto company.

173
00:08:16,400 --> 00:08:17,759
We're building a crypto exchange.

174
00:08:17,759 --> 00:08:20,319
2021 I launched bank statement converter.

175
00:08:20,319 --> 00:08:20,560
>> Okay.

176
00:08:20,560 --> 00:08:21,840
Let's talk about tech stack.

177
00:08:21,840 --> 00:08:22,960
I know you're a developer.

178
00:08:22,960 --> 00:08:26,639
Can you share with me the entire stack of how you built this app?

179
00:08:26,639 --> 00:08:28,560
The core engine is written in Cotlin.

180
00:08:28,560 --> 00:08:29,919
It's like a JVM language.

181
00:08:29,919 --> 00:08:32,159
Nex.js is what the front end is written in.

182
00:08:32,159 --> 00:08:34,560
I use Brevo for transactional emails.

183
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:37,519
I use AWS EC2 instances to host the back end.

184
00:08:37,519 --> 00:08:39,039
Netlefi to host the front end.

185
00:08:39,039 --> 00:08:40,719
Stripe for payment processing.

186
00:08:40,719 --> 00:08:41,599
And that's about it.

187
00:08:41,599 --> 00:08:42,320
a lot of profit.

188
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:45,440
It's like 39 out of $40,000 is profit.

189
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:46,480
Yeah.

190
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:46,720
>> All right.

191
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:47,920
So, you built this awesome business.

192
00:08:47,920 --> 00:08:49,680
You've been working on it for a number of years.

193
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:52,080
What have you learned in the process that surprised you?

194
00:08:52,080 --> 00:08:56,480
>> In the first two years, I was working extremely hard on the business and making basically no money.

195
00:08:56,480 --> 00:08:58,480
You know, I spent a lot of hours developing the app.

196
00:08:58,480 --> 00:09:00,720
I'd reply to customer emails as soon as possible.

197
00:09:00,720 --> 00:09:04,080
If a customer email came in at 3:00 a.m., I would deal with it right away.

198
00:09:04,080 --> 00:09:07,760
You know, at that time, every extra customer made a big impact on MR.

199
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:12,480
And what I realized was that those first two years of hard work, you don't get paid much,

200
00:09:12,480 --> 00:09:17,200
but you kind of get the money for that hard work in like years four and onwards.

201
00:09:17,200 --> 00:09:21,360
The last question that I want to ask is what we ask everyone who comes on to Starter Story.

202
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:25,279
If you could stand on Angus' shoulder when you quit your job, you're building that app.

203
00:09:25,279 --> 00:09:26,959
It was making a few dollars in revenue.

204
00:09:26,959 --> 00:09:28,399
What advice would you give him?

205
00:09:28,399 --> 00:09:30,320
>> SAS is an excellent business model.

206
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:33,600
Make sure you save enough money to survive multiple years of no income.

207
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:37,120
If you only have enough money for a few months of runway, you're probably not going to make it,

208
00:09:37,120 --> 00:09:37,360
you know?

209
00:09:37,360 --> 00:09:41,839
I mean, it took me two or three years before I could pay rent with the revenue I was getting in.

210
00:09:41,839 --> 00:09:42,800
Ignore social media.

211
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:46,959
That's, you know, a lot of people think they need to build a following on social media before building a business.

212
00:09:46,959 --> 00:09:48,320
I think it's a waste of time.

213
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:50,160
Building a following on social media is hard work.

214
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:53,600
And even if you have it, your business might still not be very good.

215
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:54,959
So, just focus on the business.

216
00:09:54,959 --> 00:09:55,839
Focus on the product.

217
00:09:55,839 --> 00:09:57,120
Get some real users.

218
00:09:57,120 --> 00:09:58,000
Improve the product.

219
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:01,120
And it should be easy to get more users if your product solves their problem.

220
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:03,760
Don't make a Facebook, Instagram, and Twitter page for your business.

221
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:06,240
See a lot of people do this, and I think it's a waste of time as well.

222
00:10:06,240 --> 00:10:07,040
That was awesome.

223
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:08,399
Thank you, Angus, for coming on.

224
00:10:08,399 --> 00:10:09,839
I love the business that you built.

225
00:10:09,839 --> 00:10:10,880
It's going to keep growing.

226
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:11,440
It's awesome.

227
00:10:11,440 --> 00:10:14,720
Thanks for sharing everything with the audience and hope to see you back on soon.

228
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:18,959
Angus is proof that you can build simple apps that actually make money.

